Choosing StrathE2E domain extent - Brazilian Shelf

Jack H Laverick, University of Strathclyde

Wednesday 25 Aug

StrathE2E contains 3 ocean volumes. Theres an inshore-offshore divide, and a shallow-deep divide. Only the offshore volume is split into shallow and deep. Choosing a shallow-deep boundary depth has knock-on consequences for the inshore-offshore divide, as the inshore zone will be defined as the sea surface to this depth. StrathE2E assumes that the volumes are well mixed, and any exchange between the deep and shallow compartments are controlled by vertical diffusivity at that depth. The boundary depth therefore needs to be deep enough to avoid excessive mixing between the volumes, while also considering how large the inshore zone will end up being. The spatial arrangement of StratheE2E is shown below.

For the Brazilian shelf we have inspected the distribution of vertical diffusivity values in the region from NEMO-MEDUSA model output. 60 m looks like a sensible depth to separate the shallow and deep layers.

As well as the vertical boundary depth, We need to choose the horizontal extent for the inshore and offshore zones of the model domain. When doing this we need to consider the following:

  • The offshore zone should extend to the continental slope.
  • Fishing activity is often high along the shelf edge, so this activity should be within in the model domain.
  • The depth limits for the inshore zone will be 0 and the minimum depth for the offshore zone.
  • The inshore zone must be an area large enough to sample NEMO-MEDUSA model outputs.

In StrathE2E terrestrial inputs can only reach the offshore zone by transiting through the inshore zone. In areas with very steep bathymetry it is possible the offshore zone polygons created above could contact land. We therefore also need to set a minimum distance from shore for the offshore zone. This ensures the inshore zone exists all along the coast. In practice this distance needs to allow a pixel of NEMO-MEDUSA model output to sit between the coast and offshore zone polygon. We chose a minimum distance from shore for the offshore zone of 20km, which typically captures the data we need.

We have suggested a 500 m maximum depth for the offshore zone as a start point, to track the contour of the continental shelf.

Finally we need to cut the polygons defined by depths and distances from shore so that they dont extend around the entire landmass. For the Brazilian shelf our first suggestion is to stop in the south with the national border of Brazil, avoiding the Rio de La Plata. In the North we suggest stopping at a latitude of 22S. If there are reasons to choose different breaks, please let us know.

To check how the proposed model domain relates to fishing activity, we plotted the cumulative fishing effort according to global fishing watch from 2017 - 2020:

The model domain is shown in grey with white borders, while the fishing effort is shown as a heatmap on a log scale. The grey area appears to capture the majority of the fishing effort within the EEZ. There is additional fishing effort along the shelf edge, just outside the model domain, Should this be included?
